/**
 * @page tutorial_networking Tutorial: Network Adapter, Messages, and Signals
 *
 * @tableofcontents
 *
 * `GameNetworkManager` is the foundation adapter that wraps the
 * kcenon `network_system` for TCP, UDP, and WebSocket game traffic.
 * It provides a unified API for binding servers, tracking sessions,
 * framing binary messages with an opcode header, and dispatching
 * incoming data to per-opcode handlers. This tutorial walks through
 * the `NetworkMessage` wire format, per-opcode handler registration,
 * the `Signal<T>` event bus used for connection lifecycle, and TLS
 * configuration for production deployments.
 *
 * **Compilable version**: `examples/10_networking.cpp` (offline
 * portions only â€” binding a real socket requires a peer; that is
 * covered by the integration test suite).
 *
 * @section tut_net_setup Setup
 *
 * @code{.cpp}
 * #include "cgs/foundation/game_network_manager.hpp"
 * #include "cgs/foundation/signal.hpp"
 * #include "cgs/foundation/types.hpp"
 *
 * using namespace cgs::foundation;
 * @endcode
 *
 * Link against `cgs::foundation_network`.
 *
 * @section tut_net_protocols Protocols and Use Cases
 *
 * @code{.cpp}
 * enum class Protocol : uint8_t { TCP, UDP, WebSocket };
 * @endcode
 *
 * | Protocol | When to use |
 * |---|---|
 * | `TCP` | Game login, chat, reliable gameplay, inventory transactions |
 * | `UDP` | Position updates, combat events, anything that tolerates drops |
 * | `WebSocket` | Browser-based clients, admin panels, metrics streams |
 *
 * One `GameNetworkManager` instance can listen on multiple
 * protocols at the same time. A typical deployment is:
 *
 * - TCP on port 8080 for login and persistent state
 * - UDP on port 8081 for position / action broadcasts
 * - WebSocket on port 9443 for admin tools
 *
 * @section tut_net_message NetworkMessage: The Wire Format
 *
 * All application-level traffic is framed as a `NetworkMessage`:
 *
 * @code{.cpp}
 * struct NetworkMessage {
 *     uint16_t opcode = 0;
 *     std::vector<uint8_t> payload;
 *
 *     std::vector<uint8_t> serialize() const;
 *     static std::optional<NetworkMessage> deserialize(const uint8_t* data, size_t size);
 *     static std::optional<NetworkMessage> deserialize(const std::vector<uint8_t>& data);
 * };
 * @endcode
 *
 * The wire format is length-prefixed:
 *
 * ```
 *  [4 bytes: total length (network order)]
 *  [2 bytes: opcode (network order)]
 *  [N bytes: payload]
 * ```
 *
 * - The 4-byte length includes the opcode bytes but not itself.
 * - Length and opcode are in network byte order, so no surprises
 *   when a client in a different endianness connects.
 * - `deserialize` returns `nullopt` for truncated or inconsistent
 *   data â€” always check before using the result.
 *
 * Construct and serialize:
 *
 * @code{.cpp}
 * NetworkMessage msg;
 * msg.opcode = 0x0100;  // project-specific
 * msg.payload.assign(text.begin(), text.end());
 *
 * std::vector<uint8_t> wire = msg.serialize();
 * @endcode
 *
 * Deserialize bytes you read from a socket:
 *
 * @code{.cpp}
 * auto decoded = NetworkMessage::deserialize(bytes);
 * if (!decoded) {
 *     // malformed â€” close the session or log and ignore
 * }
 * @endcode
 *
 * @section tut_net_opcodes Opcodes and Handlers
 *
 * Each opcode gets its own callback registered with the manager:
 *
 * @code{.cpp}
 * constexpr uint16_t kOpcodeLogin = 0x0001;
 * constexpr uint16_t kOpcodeChat = 0x0100;
 *
 * GameNetworkManager net;
 *
 * net.registerHandler(kOpcodeLogin, [](SessionId sid, const NetworkMessage& msg) {
 *     // Parse login payload, authenticate, send response.
 * });
 *
 * net.registerHandler(kOpcodeChat, [](SessionId sid, const NetworkMessage& msg) {
 *     // Broadcast chat text to recipients.
 * });
 * @endcode
 *
 * `registerHandler` overwrites any previous handler for the same
 * opcode. Use `unregisterHandler(opcode)` to remove one.
 *
 * **Organize opcodes in namespaced ranges.** A common convention:
 *
 * | Range | Purpose |
 * |---|---|
 * | `0x0000 â€“ 0x00FF` | System / heartbeat / ping |
 * | `0x0100 â€“ 0x01FF` | Authentication / session lifecycle |
 * | `0x0200 â€“ 0x02FF` | World state (positions, spawns) |
 * | `0x0300 â€“ 0x03FF` | Combat events |
 * | `0x0400 â€“ 0x04FF` | Chat, emotes, social |
 * | `0xFF00 â€“ 0xFFFF` | Admin / debug tools |
 *
 * Centralize them in `include/cgs/protocol/opcodes.hpp` so the
 * client and the server never drift.
 *
 * @section tut_net_signals Signal<T> Event Bus
 *
 * `Signal<Args...>` is the thread-safe publish/subscribe primitive
 * used by every foundation adapter. The network manager exposes
 * three lifecycle signals:
 *
 * @code{.cpp}
 * class GameNetworkManager {
 * public:
 *     Signal<SessionId> onConnected;
 *     Signal<SessionId> onDisconnected;
 *     Signal<SessionId, ErrorCode> onError;
 * };
 * @endcode
 *
 * Subscribe slots before calling `listen`:
 *
 * @code{.cpp}
 * net.onConnected.connect([](SessionId sid) {
 *     CGS_LOG_INFO(LogCategory::Network, "session connected");
 * });
 * net.onDisconnected.connect([](SessionId sid) {
 *     CGS_LOG_INFO(LogCategory::Network, "session disconnected");
 * });
 * net.onError.connect([](SessionId sid, ErrorCode code) {
 *     CGS_LOG_WARN(LogCategory::Network, "session error");
 * });
 * @endcode
 *
 * `connect` returns a `SlotId` you can use to unsubscribe:
 *
 * @code{.cpp}
 * auto slotId = net.onConnected.connect(handler);
 * // ...
 * net.onConnected.disconnect(slotId);
 * @endcode
 *
 * `Signal` uses `std::shared_mutex` internally so emission is
 * reader-concurrent. Slots run on the thread that called `emit`
 * (typically a network I/O thread) â€” marshal to the game thread
 * if you need thread affinity.
 *
 * @section tut_net_listen Listening and Stopping
 *
 * Bind to a port and start accepting connections:
 *
 * @code{.cpp}
 * auto result = net.listen(8080, Protocol::TCP);
 * if (!result) {
 *     CGS_LOG_ERROR(LogCategory::Network, result.error().message());
 *     return EXIT_FAILURE;
 * }
 * @endcode
 *
 * Common failure modes:
 *
 * | Error | Cause |
 * |---|---|
 * | `ListenFailed` | Port already in use, permission denied |
 * | `TlsNotSupported` | TLS requested on UDP or WebSocket (TCP only) |
 * | `InvalidArgument` | Port == 0 or other bad input |
 *
 * Shut down gracefully:
 *
 * @code{.cpp}
 * net.stop(Protocol::TCP);   // one protocol at a time
 * net.stopAll();             // all protocols
 * @endcode
 *
 * `stop` returns `GameResult<void>`; always check it if you care
 * about clean shutdown telemetry.
 *
 * @section tut_net_tls TLS Configuration
 *
 * Production deployments must use TLS for login and chat traffic.
 * The TLS overload of `listen` takes a `TlsConfig`:
 *
 * @code{.cpp}
 * TlsConfig tls;
 * tls.certPath = "/etc/cgs/server.crt";
 * tls.keyPath = "/etc/cgs/server.key";
 * tls.caPath = "/etc/cgs/ca.crt";       // optional, for mTLS
 * tls.verifyPeer = false;               // true for mutual TLS
 *
 * auto result = net.listen(8443, Protocol::TCP, tls);
 * @endcode
 *
 * TLS is currently supported only on `Protocol::TCP`. Requesting
 * TLS on UDP or WebSocket returns `ErrorCode::TlsNotSupported`.
 *
 * `TlsConfig::isValid()` verifies that `certPath` and `keyPath`
 * are both set. Call it before passing to `listen` to get a
 * readable error instead of a mysterious failure deep in OpenSSL.
 *
 * The framework enforces **TLS 1.3 minimum** and disables weak
 * cipher suites â€” there is no knob to downgrade. If you need
 * 1.2 compatibility, don't use this adapter.
 *
 * @section tut_net_sessions Session Tracking
 *
 * Each accepted connection gets a `SessionId` (strong typedef
 * over `uint64_t`). Look up per-session metadata:
 *
 * @code{.cpp}
 * auto info = net.sessionInfo(sid);
 * if (info) {
 *     std::cout << protocolName(info->protocol)
 *               << " from " << info->remoteAddress << "\n";
 * }
 * @endcode
 *
 * `SessionInfo` carries the protocol, remote address string, and
 * connection/last-activity timestamps. Use them for idle
 * detection and for log correlation.
 *
 * Send to a single session or broadcast:
 *
 * @code{.cpp}
 * net.send(sid, message);       // one recipient
 * net.broadcast(message);        // every connected session
 * net.close(sid);                // force-disconnect one
 * @endcode
 *
 * `sessionCount()` returns the total across all protocols â€” useful
 * for metrics dashboards.
 *
 * @section tut_net_debugging Debugging Tips
 *
 * 1. **Log the opcode on every incoming message.** Simple line
 *    like `CGS_LOG_DEBUG(LogCategory::Network, std::to_string(msg.opcode))`
 *    exposes protocol violations instantly.
 *
 * 2. **Verify the wire format with `xxd`.** The 4-byte length
 *    and 2-byte opcode should match what `serialize()` produced.
 *    If a client and the server disagree on the length, you
 *    have an endianness or framing bug.
 *
 * 3. **Trace `onDisconnected` reasons.** Losing a session
 *    silently is a common source of "players get kicked
 *    randomly" reports. Pair every disconnect with an `onError`
 *    log if applicable.
 *
 * 4. **Inspect `sessionCount()` over time.** A steady growth
 *    without corresponding `onConnected` slots firing means
 *    slots got disconnected without your code noticing.
 *
 * 5. **Put an assert in the TLS path for production.** Accidentally
 *    running the non-TLS `listen` overload in production is
 *    a data-leak risk. Add `assert(tls.isValid())` at boot time.
 *
 * @section tut_net_pitfalls Common Pitfalls
 *
 * 1. **Forgetting to check `deserialize` for `nullopt`.**
 *    Malformed data will crash a naive implementation that
 *    unwraps unconditionally. Always validate and reject.
 *
 * 2. **Thread-unsafe handler state.** Handlers can run on any
 *    I/O thread. Capture shared state by shared-pointer and
 *    protect it with a mutex, or marshal to the game thread
 *    via a queue.
 *
 * 3. **Busy-loop in a slot.** Signal slots run synchronously on
 *    the emitting thread. A slot that waits on a future blocks
 *    every other slot for the same signal. Keep slots tiny and
 *    offload work.
 *
 * 4. **Assuming opcodes are unique globally.** Different game
 *    modes can reuse the same opcode space. If you multiplex
 *    game modes on one GameNetworkManager, namespace the
 *    opcodes or use a dispatch table keyed on (mode, opcode).
 *
 * 5. **Back-pressure ignored.** `send` returns a result even
 *    when the queue is full. Always check and slow down the
 *    producer â€” otherwise memory grows unboundedly.
 *
 * 6. **Serialization versioning.** Changing the payload of an
 *    opcode without bumping a version tag breaks every client
 *    that connects with the old format. Embed a version byte
 *    at the start of each payload.
 *
 * 7. **WebSocket text vs. binary framing.** `NetworkMessage` is
 *    binary. If you use the WebSocket protocol, the framework
 *    wraps it in binary frames; a JavaScript client must
 *    receive as `ArrayBuffer`, not as a string.
 *
 * @section tut_net_performance Performance Notes
 *
 * - **`serialize` / `deserialize` allocate once** â€” a single
 *   `std::vector<uint8_t>`. Avoid doing them in tight inner
 *   loops; build messages once and broadcast.
 * - **Signal emission is `O(slots)`** with a shared-mutex read
 *   lock. ~30 ns per slot invocation in release builds.
 * - **`send` is async internally** â€” it copies the message
 *   into a per-session queue and returns immediately. The
 *   actual write happens on the I/O thread.
 * - **`broadcast` is `O(sessions)`** per call â€” consider
 *   grouping recipients by interest management (see
 *   @ref tutorial_spatial_world) to avoid broadcasting to
 *   everyone.
 * - **TLS handshake costs ~50 ms** per connection on a
 *   reasonable CPU. Warm clients that reconnect frequently
 *   should use session resumption.
 * - **Opcode dispatch is `O(log n)`** via the handler map
 *   under the hood. For hot paths with < 32 opcodes, the
 *   linear alternative is often faster due to cache effects;
 *   benchmark before micro-optimizing.
 *
 * @section tut_net_next Next Steps
 *
